ny places in England called Upton, most of which are named with Old English <i>upp</i> ‘upper’ + <i>tūn</i> ‘farmstead, estate’, though some have different origins, such as one in Essex, originally named with the phrase <i>upp in tūne</i> ‘up in the settlement’, i.e. the higher part of the settlement, and Upton Lovell (Wiltshire), which derives from the Old English personal name <i>Ubba</i> + Old English <i>tūn</i>. This name was brought to Ireland (Antrim) in 1598 by Henry <i>Upton</i>, from Upton in Devon."],"variants":[{"name":"Uptain","meanings":["Perhaps an altered form of English   Upton  ."]}]},{"name":"Ellen","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Originally a variant of   Helen  , although now no longer associated with that name. Initial <i>H-</i> tended to be added and dropped rather capriciously, leading to many doublets (  compare for example  Esther   and   Hester  ). It is also sometimes used as a short form of   Eleanor  , to which, however, it is unrelated."],"variants":[{"name":"Eleanor","meanings":["From an Old French respelling of the Old Provençal name <i>Alienor</i>. This has sometimes been taken as a derivative of   Helen  , but it is more probably of Germanic derivation (the first element being <i>ali</i> ‘other, foreign’ the second is obscure). The name was introduced to England by  Eleanor of Aquitaine  (  1122–1204 ), who came from Aquitaine in south-west France to be the wife of  King Henry II . It was also borne by Eleanor of Provence, the wife of  Henry III , and Eleanor of Castile, wife of  Edward I ."]}]},{"name":"Alice","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Originally a variant of   Adelaide  , representing an Old French spelling of a reduced form of Germanic <i>Adalheidis</i>. <i>Alice</i> and <i>Adelaide</i> were already regarded as distinct names in English during the medieval period. <i>Alice</i> enjoyed a surge of popularity in the 19th century and periods of favour ever since. It was the name of the central character of  Lewis Carroll's  Alice's Adventures in Wonderland (  1865 ) and Through the Looking Glass (  1872 ), who was based on his child friend  Alice Liddell , daughter of the Dean of Christ Church, Oxford."],"variants":[{"name":"Alys","meanings":["Variant spelling of   Alice ."]},{"name":"Alis","meanings":["equivalent of <b>Alice</b> ."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"Ellen Alice Upton was born in 1470, in England, United Kingdom as the daughter of Upton. She had at least 1 son with Roger Oliver. She died in 1530, in Shropshire, England, United Kingdom, at the age of 60."},"et":{"1470–1530":"1470–1530","1490–1584":"1490–1584","–Male":"Surnud","ABT 1530":"umbes 1530","1530":"1530","1584":"1584","1470":"1470","1490":"1490","Shropshire, England":"Shropshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","England":"Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"1470–1530":"1470–1530","1490–1584":"1490–1584","–Male":"Kuollut","ABT 1530":"noin 1530","1530":"1530","1584":"1584","1470":"1470","1490":"1490","Shropshire, England":"Shropshire, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","England":"Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta"},"fr":{"1470–1530":"1470–1530","1490–1584":"1490–1584","–Male":"Décédé","ABT 1530":"environ 1530","1530":"1530","1584":"1584","1470":"1470","1490":"1490","Shropshire, England":"Shropshire, Angleterre, Royaume-Uni","England":"Angleterre, Royaume-Uni","lifeSummary":"Ellen Alice Upton est née en 1470, à Angleterre, Royaume-Uni, fille de Upton. Elle a eu au moins 1 fils avec Roger Oliver. Elle est décédée en 1530, à Shropshire, Angleterre, Royaume-Uni, à l’âge de 60 ans."},"de":{"1470–1530":"1470–1530","1490–1584":"1490–1584","–Male":"Verstorben","ABT 1530":"um 1530","1530":"1530","1584":"1584","1470":"1470","1490":"1490","Shropshire, England":"Shropshire, England, United Kingdom","England":"England, United Kingdom","lifeSummary":"Ellen Alice Upton wur